var BOOK4_ROADMAP = {sections:[{id:'ch0s1',num:'0.1',title:'MCAT Physics: What It Actually Tests',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The MCAT does not test whether you have memorized every kinematic equation. It tests whether you understand what those equations mean and can apply them to a situation you have never seen before, often described in a passage about blood flow, the physics of a nerve impulse, or the optics of an endoscope. The physics content on the MCAT covers roughly the first two semesters of an introductory physics course, but the question style is conceptual and proportional, not computational.'},{t:'p',x:'Most MCAT physics questions are passage-based. A passage presents a physical scenario, usually with a figure or a table, and asks you to reason from it. The numbers are chosen so that estimation is possible without a calculator. A question might show a graph of pressure versus depth and ask which change doubles the gauge pressure at a given point. That is not an arithmetic problem; it is a proportional reasoning problem. Another question might describe an object moving at twice the speed and ask how its kinetic energy changes. No calculation needed: KE is proportional to v^2, so doubling v quadruples KE. The student who has internalized proportional relationships answers in seconds. The student who reaches for the full equation and plugs numbers wastes minutes.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY PHYSICS IS THE MOST TRANSFERABLE MCAT SCIENCE',x:'A student who understands conservation of energy can solve a falling ball, a roller coaster, a pendulum, and a beating ventricle with the same idea. A student who understands pressure gradients drives flow understands both Bernoulli\'s equation and why a narrowed coronary artery is dangerous. Physics rewards understanding over memorization more than any other MCAT subject, because its few laws transfer without modification to an endless variety of physical situations. Learn the ideas, not the formulas.'},{t:'p',x:'The four content movements of Book 4 match what the MCAT actually emphasizes. Mechanics (Chapters 1 through 3) is the foundation: motion, force, and the conservation laws of energy and momentum. Fluids and heat (Chapters 4 and 5) are tested heavily because of their direct medical relevance: blood pressure, cardiac output, respiratory mechanics, and metabolism all live here. Electricity and magnetism (Chapters 6 through 8) cover the physics of the nerve, the heart, and the machines that image them. Waves, light, and modern physics (Chapters 9 through 13) cover sound, optics, and the atomic physics behind every imaging modality in the clinic.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH YIELD: What the MCAT Physics Section Actually Rewards',x:'Conceptual understanding: know what each law says physically, not just algebraically. Proportional reasoning: when one variable doubles or halves, know instantly how the dependent quantity changes. Passage application: read the physical setup, identify which law or conservation principle governs it, and apply it. Unit analysis: use the units of each quantity to check your reasoning and catch errors before committing to an answer.'},{t:'p',x:'Passage-based physics questions are almost always solvable by identifying two things: which physical principle governs the situation, and what the passage is changing. Once you name the principle (say, conservation of energy or Ohm\'s law) and identify the variable being manipulated in the question stem, the answer follows from the proportional relationship in the governing equation. This two-step identification is the single most efficient approach to MCAT physics, and it is the approach this book trains in every chapter.'}],quickcheck:[]},{id:'ch0s2',num:'0.2',title:'Three Habits That Actually Move Your Score',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Most students studying physics try to memorize formulas. The ones who score well do three things differently: they use unit analysis to verify every relationship, they answer proportional questions by inspection rather than by plugging numbers, and they draw a free-body diagram before writing any force equation. These three habits are worth more than any formula sheet.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'HABIT 1: UNIT ANALYSIS',x:'Units are not bookkeeping. They are a built-in error detector. If you derive an expression for velocity and its units come out as kg*m/s^2 instead of m/s, you know you made an algebra error before you ever touch a number. On the MCAT, unit analysis lets you identify which formula applies to a question even when you cannot recall the full equation: the units of the answer tell you what product or ratio of known quantities to form. This works for any quantity: pressure (Pa = N/m^2 = kg/(m*s^2)), energy (J = kg*m^2/s^2), charge (C = A*s). Build the habit now.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'HABIT 2: PROPORTIONAL REASONING',x:'Most MCAT physics questions are really asking: when variable X changes by a factor of N, how does variable Y change? Answer this by inspection from the governing equation, not by plugging numbers. In F = ma: if mass doubles and force stays the same, acceleration halves. In KE = (1/2)*m*v^2: if speed triples, KE increases by a factor of 9 (because v^2). In Q = I*R: if resistance doubles and current stays the same, voltage doubles. Practice reading every equation as a proportional statement rather than a computational recipe.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'HABIT 3: DRAW THE FREE-BODY DIAGRAM',x:'Every force problem on the MCAT is solvable if you draw the free-body diagram (FBD) correctly. Every force problem becomes a tangle if you do not. The FBD is not optional once the problem gets complicated; it IS the problem setup. One object, all forces drawn as arrows from the center of mass, labeled with what produces each force and which direction it points. Then resolve into x and y components and apply F_net = m*a in each direction. Do not skip the diagram. Students who skip it make sign errors and miss forces. Students who draw it get the algebra right.'},{t:'p',x:'These three habits are trained continuously throughout the book. Every section that introduces a new equation asks you to verify its units. Every chapter\'s discriminator boxes are written as proportional reasoning problems. Every force and mechanics chapter begins with the FBD as the mandatory first step. By Chapter 3, the three habits should be automatic.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE: Physics Habits in Medical Practice',x:'Unit analysis is how pharmacists catch dosing errors: a drug ordered in mg/kg/day for a 70 kg patient produces a number in mg/day, and if the arithmetic gives units of mg/kg^2/day instead, the formula was applied wrong. Proportional reasoning is how physicians interpret hemodynamic data: if cardiac output drops by half and systemic resistance doubles, mean arterial pressure stays the same (MAP = CO * SVR). Free-body diagrams are used in biomechanics and orthopedics to determine the forces on joints, implants, and bones under load. These are not abstract exam skills; they are clinical thinking tools.'},{t:'list',x:['Ch 1: Kinematics and Vectors - displacement, velocity, acceleration, projectile motion','Ch 2: Forces and Newton\'s Laws - free-body diagrams, friction, ramps, gravity, orbits','Ch 3: Work, Energy, and Momentum - conservation laws, collisions, power','Ch 4: Fluids - pressure, buoyancy, continuity, Bernoulli, viscosity, blood flow','Ch 5: Thermodynamics - heat, temperature, the gas laws, heat engines, entropy','Ch 6: Electrostatics and Electric Fields - Coulomb\'s law, electric fields, potential, capacitors','Ch 7: Circuits - current, resistance, Ohm\'s law, series and parallel, RC circuits','Ch 8: Magnetism and Electromagnetic Induction - magnetic forces, Faraday\'s law, EMF','Ch 9: Waves and Periodic Motion - SHM, wave properties, superposition, resonance','Ch 10: Sound - wave speed, intensity, decibels, the Doppler effect','Ch 11: Light and Geometric Optics - reflection, refraction, lenses, mirrors, the eye','Ch 12: Atomic and Nuclear Physics - quanta, atomic spectra, radioactive decay','Ch 13: Physics in Medicine - imaging modalities and the physics of the body']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'The kinetic energy of a particle is given by KE = (1/2)*m*v^2. If the speed of the particle doubles while its mass stays the same, by what factor does its kinetic energy change?',choices:['A) It doubles, because speed doubled.','B) It increases by a factor of 4, because KE is proportional to v^2 and (2)^2 = 4.','C) It increases by a factor of 8, because both the 2 and the v^2 contribute.','D) It stays the same, because mass did not change.'],answer:1,why:'KE is proportional to v^2, with mass held constant. If v doubles, v^2 increases by a factor of 2^2 = 4, so KE increases by a factor of 4. The factor of 1/2 and the mass are both constants and cancel out when taking the ratio of new KE to old KE. This is proportional reasoning: read the equation as KE ~ v^2 and apply the scaling directly, without plugging in any numbers.'}]}]};

